The distribution of \(Y\) is binomial with parameters \(n = 500\) and \(p = 0.25\). The goal is to find a lower bound for \(P(|Y/n - 0.25| < 0.05)\).

Using Chebyshev's inequality, for a random variable \(X\) with mean \(\mu\) and variance \(\sigma^2\), \(P(|X - \mu| \geq k\sigma) \leq 1/k^2\), so \(P(|X - \mu| < k\sigma) \geq 1 - 1/k^2\).

Here, \(X = Y/n\), \(\mu = p = 0.25\), and the variance of \(Y/n\) is \(\sigma^2 = p(1-p)/n = (0.25)(0.75)/500 = 0.1875/500 = 0.000375\). The deviation is \(d = 0.05\), so \(k = d / \sigma = 0.05 / \sqrt{0.000375} \approx 2.581\), but \(k\) can be expressed in terms of the variance and deviation: \(1/k^2 = \sigma^2 / d^2 = 0.000375 / (0.05)^2 = 0.000375 / 0.0025 = 0.15\).

Thus, \(P(|Y/n - 0.25| < 0.05) \geq 1 - 0.15 = 0.85\).

