The problem involves finding the probability of at least one match in a random permutation of \(n\) balls, where a match occurs when ball \(m\) is in the \(m\)-th position when drawn. The limit of this probability as \(n\) approaches infinity is required.

The probability of at least one match is given by the inclusion-exclusion principle:
\[
P(\text{at least one match}) = \sum_{k=1}^{n} (-1)^{k+1} \frac{1}{k!}
\]
As \(n \to \infty\), this sum converges to:
\[
\lim_{n \to \infty} \sum_{k=1}^{n} (-1)^{k+1} \frac{1}{k!} = 1 - \frac{1}{e}
\]
where \(e \approx 2.71828\). Numerically,
\[
