The energy of one mole of photons is calculated using the formula \(E = \frac{hcN_A}{\lambda}\), where \(h\) is Planck's constant (\(6.626 \times 10^{-34}  \text{J s}\)), \(c\) is the speed of light (\(3.00 \times 10^8  \text{m/s}\)), \(N_A\) is Avogadro's number (\(6.022 \times 10^{23}  \text{mol}^{-1}\)), and \(\lambda\) is the wavelength in meters. The wavelength is \(300  \text{nm} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7}  \text{m}\).

First, calculate the energy for one photon:  
\[
E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{hc}{\lambda} = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8)}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 6.626 \times 10^{-19}  \text{J}.
\]

Then, for one mole of photons:  
\[
E_{\text{mol}} = E_{\text{photon}} \times N_A = (6.626 \times 10^{-19}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23}) = 3.990 \times 10^5  \text{J/mol}.
\]

Convert to kJ/mol (1 kJ = 1000 J):  
\[
E_{\text{mol}} = \frac{3.990 \times 10^5}{1000} = 399  \text{kJ/mol}.
\]

