Since \(X\) and \(Y\) are independent and normally distributed, the difference \(X - Y\) follows a normal distribution. The mean of \(X - Y\) is \(\mu_X - \mu_Y = 5 - 6 = -1\), and the variance is \(\sigma_X^2 + \sigma_Y^2 = 16 + 9 = 25\). Thus, \(X - Y \sim N(-1, 25)\), and the standard deviation is \(\sqrt{25} = 5\).

To find \(P(X - Y > 0)\), standardize the variable:
\[
P(X - Y > 0) = P\left( \frac{(X - Y) - (-1)}{5} > \frac{0 - (-1)}{5} \right) = P\left( Z > \frac{1}{5} \right) = P(Z > 0.2),
\]
where \(Z\) is a standard normal random variable.

Using the standard normal distribution, \(P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - P(Z \leq 0.2)\). From standard normal tables, \(P(Z \leq 0.2) \approx 0.5793\), so:
\[
P(Z > 0.2) = 1 - 0.5793 = 0.4207.
\]

The result is rounded to four decimal places, as is common for probabilities.

