Solution: The ionization energy of \(\mathrm{H}_2\) is calculated using the given dissociation energies and the known ionization energy of the hydrogen atom. The dissociation energy \(D_0\) for \(\mathrm{H}_2\) is \(4.478 \, \mathrm{eV}\), and for \(\mathrm{H}_2^+\), it is \(2.651 \, \mathrm{eV}\). The ionization energy of a hydrogen atom (\(\mathrm{H} \rightarrow \mathrm{H}^+ + \mathrm{e}^-\)) is \(13.598 \, \mathrm{eV}\).

